<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:255px;"><a href="/wiki/File:NASA-Aeroponics_International-lettuce-day30.jpg" class="image" title="Close-up of lettuce and wheat grown in an aeroponic (air-culture) apparatus, NASA1998"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/3/35/NASA-Aeroponics_International-lettuce-day30.jpg" width="253" height="257" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">Close-up of lettuce and wheat grown in an aeroponic (air-culture) apparatus, NASA1998</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Aeroponics</b> is the process of growing <a href="/wiki/Plants" title="Plants" class="mw-redirect">plants</a> in an <a href="/wiki/Air" title="Air" class="mw-redirect">air</a> or <a href="/wiki/Mist" title="Mist">mist</a> environment without the use of <a href="/wiki/Soil" title="Soil">soil</a> or an <a href="/wiki/Construction_aggregate" title="Construction aggregate">aggregate</a> medium. Aeroponic culture differs from both <a href="/wiki/Hydroponics" title="Hydroponics">hydroponics</a> and in-vitro (<a href="/wiki/Plant_tissue_culture" title="Plant tissue culture">Plant tissue culture</a>) growing. Unlike <a href="/wiki/Hydroponics" title="Hydroponics">hydroponics</a>, which uses water as a growing medium and essential minerals to sustain plant growth, aeroponics is conducted without a growing medium.<sup id="cite_ref-stoner-clawson1_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stoner-clawson1-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
